>

  <section class="pg-hero">
    <h1>How Much Vitamin D Should I Take? The Evidence-Based Dosage Guide</h1>
    <p class="pg-sub">Most adults need 600-2,000 IU of vitamin D daily, but the optimal dose depends on your age, weight, sun exposure, and current blood levels. An estimated 42% of American adults are vitamin D deficient, with rates even higher among those with darker skin (82%), obesity (50%), and older adults (70%). This guide covers exact dosages by age, deficiency symptoms, target blood levels, and the best sources — including gummies.</p>
    <div class="pg-meta">
      <span>Updated April 2026</span>
      <span>23 Clinical Studies Reviewed</span>
      <span>Registered Dietitian Authored</span>
    </div>
  </section>

  <Breadcrumbs items={[
    { label: 'Blog', href: '/blog/' },
    { label: 'How Much Vitamin D Should I Take', href: '/blog/how-much-vitamin-d-should-i-take/' },
  ]} />

  <div class="w">

    <AuthorBox
      publishDate="2026-04-10"
      updateDate="2026-04-10"
      authorName="Sarah Mitchell"
      authorCredentials="RD, CNS"
      authorImage="/images/authors/sarah-mitchell.webp"
      authorBio="Sarah is a registered dietitian and certified nutrition specialist with 12 years of experience in supplement science. She leads GummyGuide's testing methodology."
    />

    <AffiliateDisclaimer />

    <!-- QUICK ANSWER — optimized for AI Overviews and featured snippet -->
    <div class="callout">
      <strong>Quick answer:</strong> Most adults should take 600-2,000 IU of vitamin D3 daily. The NIH recommends 600 IU for adults under 70 and 800 IU for adults over 70, but the Endocrine Society recommends 1,500-2,000 IU to maintain optimal blood levels above 30 ng/mL. People who are obese, have darker skin, live at northern latitudes, or have documented deficiency may need 2,000-4,000 IU daily. Always get a 25(OH)D blood test before starting high-dose supplementation.
      <cite>— Sarah Mitchell, RD, CNS, based on systematic review of 23 clinical trials and NIH/Endocrine Society guidelines</cite>
    </div>

    <p>Vitamin D is one of the most critical — and most commonly deficient — nutrients in the American diet. Often called the "sunshine vitamin," it functions more like a hormone than a traditional vitamin, influencing over 1,000 genes involved in calcium metabolism, immune regulation, mood, muscle function, and cellular growth. Despite its importance, an estimated 42% of American adults have blood levels classified as deficient (below 20 ng/mL), with prevalence rates reaching 82% among Black Americans and 69% among Hispanic Americans according to data from the National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey (NHANES).</p>

    <p>The consequences of vitamin D deficiency extend far beyond weak bones. Research has linked low vitamin D status to increased risk of respiratory infections, autoimmune diseases, depression, cardiovascular disease, and certain cancers. Yet confusion about dosage remains widespread — how much should you actually take? The answer depends on your age, body weight, skin color, sun exposure, and current blood levels. This guide provides the evidence-based recommendations from major medical organizations and clinical trials so you can make an informed decision. If you are looking for product recommendations, see our guides to the <a href="/vitamins/vitamin-d-gummies/">best vitamin D gummies</a> and <a href="/vitamins/best-vitamin-d3-gummies-for-adults/">best vitamin D3 gummies for adults</a>.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">42%</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">of American adults are vitamin D deficient (25(OH)D below 20 ng/mL). Rates are even higher among Black Americans (82%), Hispanic Americans (69%), adults over 65 (70%), and individuals with obesity (50%). <strong>Source: National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey (NHANES), 2005-2006 data, published in Nutrition Research.</strong></p>
    </div>

    <!-- SECTION 1: RECOMMENDED DOSAGE BY AGE -->
    <h2>Recommended Vitamin D Dosage by Age</h2>

    <p>Vitamin D dosage recommendations vary between organizations because they define "sufficiency" differently. The NIH Institute of Medicine (IOM) set the Recommended Dietary Allowance (RDA) to prevent bone disease at blood levels of 20 ng/mL — a relatively low bar. The Endocrine Society, which focuses on optimal health outcomes including immune function and disease prevention, recommends higher intakes to achieve blood levels of 30-50 ng/mL. The table below presents both sets of recommendations so you can see the range.</p>

    <div class="tbl-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Age Group</th>
            <th>NIH RDA (IU/day)</th>
            <th>Endocrine Society (IU/day)</th>
            <th>Upper Limit (IU/day)</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr class="hl">
            <td><strong>Infants (0-12 months)</strong></td>
            <td>400</td>
            <td>400-1,000</td>
            <td>1,000-1,500</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Children (1-8 years)</strong></td>
            <td>600</td>
            <td>600-1,000</td>
            <td>2,500-3,000</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="hl">
            <td><strong>Teens (9-18 years)</strong></td>
            <td>600</td>
            <td>600-1,000</td>
            <td>4,000</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Adults (19-70 years)</strong></td>
            <td>600</td>
            <td>1,500-2,000</td>
            <td>4,000</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="hl">
            <td><strong>Adults (71+ years)</strong></td>
            <td>800</td>
            <td>1,500-2,000</td>
            <td>4,000</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Pregnant / Lactating</strong></td>
            <td>600</td>
            <td>1,500-2,000</td>
            <td>4,000</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="hl">
            <td><strong>Obese adults (BMI &gt;30)</strong></td>
            <td>600</td>
            <td>2,000-4,000*</td>
            <td>4,000-10,000*</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p>*Obese individuals require 2-3 times more vitamin D than normal-weight adults because vitamin D is sequestered in adipose (fat) tissue and has reduced bioavailability. The Endocrine Society's 2011 Clinical Practice Guidelines specifically recommend that obese adults may need 6,000-10,000 IU daily to correct deficiency, followed by maintenance doses of 3,000-6,000 IU daily — all under physician supervision with periodic blood level monitoring.</p>

    <div class="tip-box">
      <span class="tip-box-ico">💡</span>
      <p><strong>Unit conversion:</strong> 1 mcg of vitamin D = 40 IU. If your supplement label uses micrograms (mcg), multiply by 40 to convert to International Units (IU). For example, 50 mcg = 2,000 IU. Most clinical guidelines and research papers use IU, while newer supplement labels increasingly use mcg as required by updated FDA labeling regulations.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="tip-box" style="background:#F1F8E9;border-color:#AED581;">
      <div class="tip-box-ico" style="background:#4CAF50;">★</div>
      <div>
        <p><strong>Our #1 Pick: Nature Made Vitamin D3 Gummies</strong></p>
        <p style="margin-top:4px;">2000 IU D3, USP verified for purity and potency. <a href="/vitamins/vitamin-d-gummies/" style="color:#2E7D32;font-weight:600;">See full review & buy →</a></p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- SECTION 2: DEFICIENCY SIGNS AND SYMPTOMS -->
    <h2>Vitamin D Deficiency: 8 Signs and Symptoms</h2>

    <p>Vitamin D deficiency develops gradually and often goes undiagnosed for years because its symptoms mimic those of stress, aging, and general fatigue. Many physicians do not routinely test vitamin D levels unless a patient specifically requests it. If you experience three or more of the following symptoms, ask your doctor to order a 25-hydroxyvitamin D blood test.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="battery" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>1. Persistent Fatigue</h4>
        <p>Unexplained tiredness that does not improve with adequate sleep is one of the most common symptoms. A study in the North American Journal of Medical Sciences found that 77% of patients who reported chronic fatigue had suboptimal vitamin D levels. Correcting the deficiency significantly improved energy levels.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="activity" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>2. Bone and Joint Pain</h4>
        <p>Vitamin D is essential for calcium absorption. Without it, bones soften and weaken — a condition called osteomalacia in adults. Chronic bone pain, particularly in the lower back, hips, and legs, is a hallmark sign. Osteomalacia is frequently misdiagnosed as fibromyalgia or arthritis.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="zap" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>3. Muscle Weakness</h4>
        <p>Vitamin D receptors are present in skeletal muscle tissue. Deficiency causes proximal muscle weakness — difficulty climbing stairs, rising from a chair, or lifting objects overhead. In older adults, this weakness increases fall risk by up to 72% according to a meta-analysis in Molecular Aspects of Medicine.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="moon" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>4. Depression and Low Mood</h4>
        <p>Vitamin D receptors are concentrated in brain regions involved in mood regulation, including the prefrontal cortex and hippocampus. A 2013 meta-analysis in the British Journal of Psychiatry found that low vitamin D levels were associated with a significantly increased risk of depression. Supplementation improved depressive symptoms in deficient individuals.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="alert-circle" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>5. Hair Loss</h4>
        <p>Vitamin D stimulates hair follicle cycling. Severe deficiency has been linked to alopecia areata — an autoimmune condition that causes patchy hair loss. While hair loss has many causes, vitamin D deficiency should be ruled out as a contributing factor, especially in women experiencing diffuse thinning.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="clock" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>6. Slow Wound Healing</h4>
        <p>Vitamin D plays a direct role in the inflammatory and antimicrobial phases of wound healing. It promotes the production of cathelicidin, an antimicrobial peptide that protects wounds from infection. Deficient individuals experience slower healing times after surgery, injury, or dental procedures.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="shield" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>7. Frequent Illness and Infection</h4>
        <p>Vitamin D activates T cells, macrophages, and natural killer cells — key components of both innate and adaptive immunity. People with blood levels below 20 ng/mL are 40% more likely to develop upper respiratory infections according to a study in Archives of Internal Medicine. Frequent colds, flu, and bronchitis may signal deficiency.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="heart" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>8. Chronic Back Pain</h4>
        <p>Vitamin D deficiency is an under-recognized cause of chronic lower back pain. A 2015 meta-analysis found that patients with chronic back pain had significantly lower vitamin D levels than pain-free controls. Supplementation reduced pain severity in deficient patients, suggesting that vitamin D testing should be standard in chronic pain workups.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- SECTION 3: TARGET BLOOD LEVELS -->
    <h2>What Blood Level of Vitamin D Should You Target?</h2>

    <p>The only reliable way to assess your vitamin D status is a 25-hydroxyvitamin D [25(OH)D] blood test — also called a calcidiol test. This measures the circulating form of vitamin D in your bloodstream and reflects both dietary intake and sun-derived synthesis. Most laboratories and clinical guidelines use the following classification ranges.</p>

    <div class="tbl-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Blood Level (ng/mL)</th>
            <th>Blood Level (nmol/L)</th>
            <th>Classification</th>
            <th>Health Impact</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>&lt;12</strong></td>
            <td>&lt;30</td>
            <td>Severely Deficient</td>
            <td>Rickets (children), osteomalacia (adults), severely impaired immunity</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="hl">
            <td><strong>12-20</strong></td>
            <td>30-50</td>
            <td>Deficient</td>
            <td>Increased bone loss, impaired calcium absorption, higher infection risk</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>20-30</strong></td>
            <td>50-75</td>
            <td>Insufficient</td>
            <td>Suboptimal bone health and immune function, higher disease risk</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="hl">
            <td><strong>30-50</strong></td>
            <td>75-125</td>
            <td>Sufficient (Optimal)</td>
            <td>Optimal calcium absorption, bone density, immune function, and mood</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>50-100</strong></td>
            <td>125-250</td>
            <td>High (No additional benefit)</td>
            <td>No proven benefit over 30-50 range; may increase calcium-related risks</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="hl">
            <td><strong>&gt;150</strong></td>
            <td>&gt;375</td>
            <td>Toxic</td>
            <td>Hypercalcemia, kidney damage, nausea, vomiting, confusion</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">30-50 ng/mL</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">is the target range recommended by the Endocrine Society, American Geriatrics Society, and National Osteoporosis Foundation for optimal health outcomes including bone density, immune function, cardiovascular health, and cancer risk reduction.</p>
    </div>

    <p>If your blood level is below 20 ng/mL, your physician may prescribe a high-dose loading protocol — typically 50,000 IU of vitamin D2 or D3 once weekly for 8-12 weeks — followed by maintenance dosing of 1,500-2,000 IU daily. If your level is between 20-30 ng/mL, daily supplementation of 1,500-2,000 IU is usually sufficient to raise levels into the optimal range within 2-3 months. Retest your 25(OH)D level after 3 months of supplementation to verify you have reached the target range.</p>

    <!-- SECTION 4: D3 VS D2 -->
    <h2>Vitamin D3 vs D2: Which Should You Take?</h2>

    <p>Not all vitamin D is created equal. The two supplemental forms — D3 (cholecalciferol) and D2 (ergocalciferol) — differ significantly in potency, half-life, and effectiveness at raising blood levels. The clinical evidence strongly favors D3 for supplementation.</p>

    <div class="tbl-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Factor</th>
            <th>Vitamin D3 (Cholecalciferol)</th>
            <th>Vitamin D2 (Ergocalciferol)</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr class="hl">
            <td><strong>Source</strong></td>
            <td>Animal-based: fatty fish, egg yolks, lanolin (sheep wool), lichen (vegan D3)</td>
            <td>Plant/fungal: UV-irradiated mushrooms, yeast</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Potency</strong></td>
            <td>87% more effective at raising 25(OH)D blood levels</td>
            <td>Less potent per IU; requires higher doses for equivalent effect</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="hl">
            <td><strong>Half-life</strong></td>
            <td>~2-3 weeks — maintains stable blood levels longer</td>
            <td>~2 weeks — shorter duration, drops faster between doses</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Bioavailability</strong></td>
            <td>Higher binding affinity to vitamin D-binding protein (DBP)</td>
            <td>Lower DBP binding; more rapid clearance from circulation</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="hl">
            <td><strong>Vegan Options</strong></td>
            <td>Yes — lichen-derived D3 is plant-based and equally effective</td>
            <td>Yes — all D2 is plant-derived</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Clinical Recommendation</strong></td>
            <td>Preferred by Endocrine Society and most clinical guidelines</td>
            <td>Acceptable alternative; commonly used in prescription form</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p>A landmark 2012 meta-analysis published in the <em>American Journal of Clinical Nutrition</em> analyzed 10 randomized controlled trials and concluded that D3 was 87% more potent than D2 at raising serum 25(OH)D concentrations. D3 also produced more stable, sustained blood levels over time compared to D2, which tended to spike and drop more rapidly. For these reasons, D3 is the universally recommended form for supplementation. If you follow a strict vegan diet, lichen-derived vitamin D3 is now widely available and delivers the same efficacy as animal-sourced D3. Browse our top picks in our <a href="/vitamins/best-vitamin-d3-gummies-for-adults/">best vitamin D3 gummies for adults</a> guide.</p>

    <!-- SECTION 5: BEST SOURCES OF VITAMIN D -->
    <h2>Best Sources of Vitamin D</h2>

    <p>Vitamin D is available from three sources: sunlight, food, and supplements. For most Americans, supplements are the most reliable way to maintain optimal levels because sun exposure is inconsistent and few foods contain meaningful amounts. Here is a breakdown of each source.</p>

    <h3>Sunlight</h3>

    <p>When UVB radiation from sunlight strikes the skin, it converts 7-dehydrocholesterol into previtamin D3, which is then transformed into active vitamin D3. Fair-skinned individuals can produce 10,000-20,000 IU from just 10-30 minutes of midday sun exposure with arms and legs uncovered. However, numerous factors dramatically reduce this production:</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="shield" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Sunscreen</h4>
        <p>SPF 30 blocks 97% of UVB rays. SPF 50 blocks 98%. While dermatologists rightfully recommend sunscreen for skin cancer prevention, consistent use virtually eliminates vitamin D synthesis from sun exposure.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="calendar" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Latitude and Season</h4>
        <p>People living above 37 degrees north latitude (roughly from San Francisco to Philadelphia) cannot produce meaningful vitamin D from sunlight between November and February because UVB rays are too weak. This affects approximately 70% of the US population.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="star" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Skin Pigmentation</h4>
        <p>Melanin acts as a natural sunscreen. People with darker skin need 3-6 times more sun exposure to produce the same amount of vitamin D as fair-skinned individuals. This is a primary reason why 82% of Black Americans are vitamin D deficient.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="clock" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Age</h4>
        <p>Skin's capacity to produce vitamin D decreases with age. A 70-year-old produces approximately 25% of the vitamin D that a 20-year-old produces from the same sun exposure. This contributes to the 70% deficiency rate among older adults.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3>Food Sources</h3>

    <div class="tbl-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Food</th>
            <th>Serving Size</th>
            <th>Vitamin D (IU)</th>
            <th>% Daily Value</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr class="hl">
            <td><strong>Cod liver oil</strong></td>
            <td>1 tablespoon</td>
            <td>1,360</td>
            <td>227%</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Wild-caught salmon</strong></td>
            <td>3 oz cooked</td>
            <td>570</td>
            <td>95%</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="hl">
            <td><strong>Canned tuna</strong></td>
            <td>3 oz drained</td>
            <td>240</td>
            <td>40%</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>UV-exposed mushrooms</strong></td>
            <td>1 cup sliced</td>
            <td>366</td>
