    <p>As the table illustrates, very few foods contain enough vitamin D to meet the recommended intake without supplementation. You would need to eat 3-4 servings of wild-caught salmon daily to reach 2,000 IU from food alone — which is neither practical nor affordable for most people. This is why the Endocrine Society states that most adults need vitamin D supplements to achieve optimal blood levels.</p>

    <h3>Supplements</h3>

    <p>Vitamin D supplements are the most reliable, consistent, and cost-effective way to maintain optimal 25(OH)D levels. They are available in capsules, soft gels, drops, and gummies. For taste, convenience, and compliance, gummies have become the most popular format — particularly for people who dislike swallowing pills. Our comprehensive <a href="/vitamins/vitamin-d-gummies/">vitamin D gummies</a> guide reviews the top products on the market with dose accuracy testing and third-party verification data.</p>

    <!-- SECTION 6: VITAMIN D AND IMMUNE HEALTH -->
    <h2>Vitamin D and Immune Health</h2>

    <p>The connection between vitamin D and immune function is one of the most extensively researched areas in nutritional science. Vitamin D receptors (VDRs) are expressed on virtually every cell of the immune system — including T cells, B cells, macrophages, dendritic cells, and natural killer cells. Without adequate vitamin D, these immune cells cannot activate and function properly.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="shield" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Innate Immunity</h4>
        <p>Vitamin D triggers the production of cathelicidin and defensins — antimicrobial peptides that directly kill bacteria, viruses, and fungi. This is the body's first line of defense against pathogens and explains why vitamin D deficiency is associated with higher rates of respiratory infections.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="zap" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Adaptive Immunity</h4>
        <p>Vitamin D modulates T cell and B cell responses, helping the immune system mount an effective defense while preventing overreaction. This dual role is critical — an immune system that overreacts causes autoimmune disease, while one that underreacts allows infections to persist.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="alert-triangle" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Respiratory Infection Prevention</h4>
        <p>A landmark 2017 meta-analysis in the BMJ analyzed 25 randomized controlled trials with 11,321 participants and found that daily or weekly vitamin D supplementation reduced the risk of acute respiratory infections by 12% overall — and by 70% in participants who were severely deficient (&lt;10 ng/mL) at baseline.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="heart" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>COVID-19 Research</h4>
        <p>Multiple observational studies during the COVID-19 pandemic found that patients with vitamin D deficiency had significantly higher rates of hospitalization, ICU admission, and mortality. While vitamin D is not a treatment for COVID-19, maintaining adequate levels (30-50 ng/mL) supports the immune response to respiratory viruses including SARS-CoV-2.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

