    <!-- SECTION 7: VITAMIN D AND SLEEP -->
    <h2>Vitamin D and Sleep Quality</h2>

    <p>An emerging body of research links vitamin D status to sleep quality — a connection that makes physiological sense when you consider the mechanisms involved. Vitamin D receptors are expressed in brain regions that regulate sleep, including the hypothalamus and brainstem, and vitamin D influences the production of serotonin — the precursor to melatonin, the body's primary sleep hormone.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="moon" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Melatonin Production</h4>
        <p>Vitamin D is required for the expression of tryptophan hydroxylase 2 (TPH2), the enzyme that converts tryptophan into serotonin in the brain. Serotonin is then converted to melatonin by the pineal gland. When vitamin D levels are low, serotonin production falls, and melatonin synthesis is impaired — disrupting the circadian rhythm.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="star" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Sleep Quality Studies</h4>
        <p>A 2018 meta-analysis in <em>Nutrients</em> analyzing 9 studies with 9,397 participants found that vitamin D deficiency was associated with a significantly higher risk of sleep disorders, including shorter sleep duration, poorer sleep quality, and increased daytime sleepiness. Supplementation improved sleep outcomes in deficient individuals.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>If you are experiencing poor sleep alongside symptoms of vitamin D deficiency, correcting the deficiency may improve your sleep quality without the need for dedicated sleep supplements. For comprehensive sleep support, explore our <a href="/best-sleep-gummies/">best sleep gummies</a> guide, which covers melatonin, magnesium, L-theanine, and herbal formulas. You may also find our in-depth article on <a href="/blog/magnesium-for-sleep/">magnesium for sleep</a> helpful, as magnesium works through complementary sleep pathways.</p>

    <!-- SECTION 8: CAN YOU TAKE TOO MUCH? -->
    <h2>Can You Take Too Much Vitamin D?</h2>

    <p>Yes. While vitamin D toxicity from food or sunlight is virtually impossible, it can occur from excessive supplementation. The NIH Tolerable Upper Intake Level (UL) is 4,000 IU daily for adults — exceeding this amount chronically without medical supervision increases the risk of adverse effects.</p>

    <div class="warn-box">
      <span class="warn-box-ico">⚠️</span>
      <p><strong>Vitamin D toxicity warning:</strong> Taking more than 10,000 IU daily for extended periods without medical supervision can cause vitamin D toxicity (hypervitaminosis D). Symptoms include nausea, vomiting, poor appetite, constipation, weakness, weight loss, and — most dangerously — hypercalcemia (elevated blood calcium). Hypercalcemia can lead to calcium deposits in the kidneys (kidney stones), blood vessels (arterial calcification), and heart, potentially causing kidney failure, cardiac arrhythmia, and death in severe cases. <strong>Never take more than 4,000 IU daily unless directed by a physician with periodic blood level monitoring.</strong></p>
    </div>

