    <!-- FAQ -->
    <section class="faq-sec">
      <h2>How Much Vitamin D Should I Take — Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details class="fq"><summary>How much vitamin D should I take daily?</summary><p>Most adults need 600-2,000 IU of vitamin D daily. The NIH RDA is 600 IU for adults under 70 and 800 IU for those over 70. The Endocrine Society recommends 1,500-2,000 IU to maintain blood levels above 30 ng/mL. People who are obese, have darker skin, or have documented deficiency may need 2,000-4,000 IU under physician guidance.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>What are the signs of vitamin D deficiency?</summary><p>Common signs include persistent fatigue, bone and joint pain, muscle weakness, depression, hair loss, slow wound healing, frequent infections, and chronic back pain. These symptoms overlap with many conditions, so a 25(OH)D blood test is the only reliable way to confirm deficiency. Levels below 20 ng/mL are classified as deficient.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Is 5,000 IU of vitamin D too much?</summary><p>For most healthy adults, 5,000 IU daily exceeds the NIH Upper Limit of 4,000 IU but is commonly prescribed to correct documented deficiency. Short-term use is generally safe, but long-term use without blood monitoring can cause toxicity including hypercalcemia and kidney stones. Do not take 5,000 IU daily without physician supervision.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>What is the difference between vitamin D2 and D3?</summary><p>Vitamin D3 (cholecalciferol) is 87% more effective than D2 (ergocalciferol) at raising blood levels. D3 has a longer half-life and higher binding affinity to vitamin D-binding protein. D3 is the recommended form for supplementation. Vegan D3 from lichen is available for plant-based diets.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Can you get enough vitamin D from the sun?</summary><p>It is possible but unlikely for most Americans. Sunscreen, latitude, season, skin pigmentation, age, and indoor lifestyles all reduce vitamin D synthesis. An estimated 42% of Americans are deficient despite abundant sunlight, which demonstrates that sun exposure alone is insufficient for most people.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>What blood level of vitamin D is optimal?</summary><p>The optimal range is 30-50 ng/mL (75-125 nmol/L). Below 20 ng/mL is deficient and increases risk of bone disease, immune dysfunction, and depression. Between 20-30 ng/mL is insufficient. Above 50 ng/mL offers no additional benefit. Above 150 ng/mL is considered toxic.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Should I take vitamin D with vitamin K2?</summary><p>Yes, especially at doses above 1,000 IU daily. Vitamin D increases calcium absorption, while K2 directs that calcium into bones rather than arteries and kidneys. A typical pairing is 2,000 IU D3 with 100-200 mcg K2 (MK-7). Many quality supplements now include both.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Are vitamin D gummies as effective as capsules?</summary><p>Yes. Vitamin D is absorbed through the GI tract regardless of delivery format. Gummies, capsules, and liquid drops all deliver vitamin D effectively when taken with a fat-containing meal. The advantage of gummies is higher compliance — people take them consistently because they taste good. The most important factor is D3 vs D2 and the IU per serving.</p></details>
    </section>

