    <div class="verdict">
      <h3>The Evidence-Based Verdict: How Much Vitamin D Should You Take?</h3>
      <p>For most adults, 1,500-2,000 IU of vitamin D3 daily is the sweet spot recommended by the Endocrine Society to maintain blood levels in the optimal 30-50 ng/mL range. The NIH RDA of 600-800 IU prevents severe deficiency but may be insufficient for optimal immune function, mood regulation, and disease prevention based on current evidence. People who are obese, have darker skin, are over 65, or get minimal sun exposure likely need 2,000-4,000 IU daily.</p>
      <p>With 42% of Americans deficient, correcting vitamin D status is one of the most impactful, affordable, and low-risk interventions available. Get a 25(OH)D blood test to establish your baseline, choose a D3 supplement (preferably paired with K2), take it with a fat-containing meal for maximum absorption, and retest after 3 months. Vitamin D gummies offer the highest compliance rate and make daily supplementation easy and enjoyable.</p>
